defaultDear Sir/Madam
default&#xa0;
defaultWidening the debatedefault&#xa0;defaultI discovered by chance the invitation to comment on the Draft Deregulation Bill while looking at the Red Tape Challenge website. I was concerned to read that it was proposed that there may be a duty to promote economic growth – on a planet of finite resources – perhaps not the best idea. Of course there are no easy answers, 
defaultbut accepting the limits to growth would certainly help to appraise alternatives
default.  There are many different viewpoints and I would hope the debate was wider so that other viewpoints could be considered and “flaws” ironed out. The time scale for the debate should not be fixed so to speak at 3 months. It should be ongoing.
default&#xa0;
defaultMany people, economists
default8
default and organisations with something important to say will be unaware of the consultation, 
defaultsuch as CASSE
default9
default (the Centre for the Advancement of a Steady State Economy)
default. The deadline should be extended and the debate ongoing.
default I would like to make some general comments.
default&#xa0;
defaultI believe there are fundamental flaws in the concept of the red tape challenge, for example the embarrassing list of members interests on the ACRE
default13
default web site. 
defaultWill the introduction of a duty to have 
defaultregard
default to “promoting economic growth” compromise the independence of regulators? What additional safeguards are required to ensure that the introduction of such a duty will not compromise the independence of a 
defaultregulator.
default  
defaultI feel there is
default no truedefault or limited “independence” with regard to food safety regulators for example and many food sovereignty and humanitarian organisations, members of the public and NGOs are aware of this. FSA, FDA, EFSA.... revolving doors ......
default  all have come under harsh criticism despite some good work in some areas.
default&#xa0;
defaultI disagree that there should be legislation with regard to a “
defaultduty 
defaultto promote economic growth”.  I would not acknowledge such legislation neither would many others.
defaultThe various view points of the individuals and organisations listed below should be taken into 
defaultaccount
default.
default&#xa0;defaultLeave no stone unturneddefaultThere are many other organisations and individuals that I have not listed which would be able to provide feedback and alternative view points to those proposed. Lord Heseltine and Milton Friedman are not of course the only people to have ever held an opinion, leave no stone unturned!
default&#xa0;
defaultViewpointsdefaultNaomi Klein – author of The Shock Doctrine
default2 
defaultand No Logo (international best seller)
defaultPolly Higgins – Ecocide is a crime
default1
default, I would add to Polly’s view point that we are all responsible in one sense.
default....The United Nations is to discuss, approve and promote among the Member States an International Ecocide Convention, aiming to protect the Earth and its living species and hold legally accountable institutions, organisms, organisations and their leaders.....
